# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-data-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-data-systems/adata] In 2016, ADATA was the second-largest DRAM module manufacturer in the world by revenue and had a market capitalization of US$680 million.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/adata] In recent years, ADATA has extended its business to Europe and the Americas, while competing strongly with Samsung in Asia.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is best known as the world's biggest online shopping retailer and marketplace, offering a wide range of products and services.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon sells books, electronics, pharmaceuticals, car parts, video games, dining products, jewelry, food, music, and sports equipment.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The company has multiple subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services (AWS), which provides cloud computing; Zoox, a self-driving car division; Kuiper Systems, a satellite Internet provider; and Amazon Lab126, a computer hardware R&D provider.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Other subsidiaries include Ring, Twitch, IMDb, and Whole Foods Market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Its acquisition of Whole Foods in August 2017 for US$13.4 billion substantially increased its market share and its presence as a physical retailer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon also distributes a variety of downloadable and streaming content through its Amazon Prime Video, MGM+, Amazon Music, Twitch, Audible, and Wondery units.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon also produces consumer electronics, most notably Kindle e-readers, Echo devices, Fire tablets, and Fire TVs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon has a reputation as a disruptor of industries through technological innovation and aggressive reinvestment of profits into capital expenditures.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of 2023, it is the world's largest online retailer and marketplace, smart speaker provider, cloud computing service provider through AWS, live-streaming service provider through Twitch, and Internet company as measured by revenue and market share.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2021, it surpassed Walmart as the world's largest retailer outside of China, driven in large part by its paid subscription plan, Amazon Prime, which has 200 million subscribers worldwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is the second-largest private employer in the United States and the second-largest company in the world and the United States by revenue as of 2024 (after Walmart).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of October 2024, Amazon is the 12th-most visited website in the world, and 84% of its traffic comes from the United States.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon has been criticized for its business practices, including surveillance partnerships, poor working conditions, anti-union efforts, environmental harm, anticompetitive behavior, censorship controversies, and exploitative treatment of small businesses and suppliers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On July 5, 1994, Amazon was founded as "Cadabra" by Jeff Bezos, after he relocated from New York City to Bellevue, Washington, near Seattle, to operate an online bookstore.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Bezos chose the Seattle area for its abundance of technical talent from Microsoft and the University of Washington, as well as its smaller population for sales tax purposes and the proximity to a major book distribution warehouse in Roseburg, Oregon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Other options Bezos considered included Portland, Oregon, and Boulder, Colorado.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] A few months later, in November 1994, Cadabra, which had been founded in the converted garage of Bezos's house for symbolic reasons, was renamed to Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On July 16, 1995, the Amazon website launched for public sales, initially sourcing its books directly from wholesalers and publishers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Bezos retained the URL www.relentless.com, which he purchased when considering a name for the company; it redirects to the Amazon homepage.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 1998, Amazon began selling music and videos, and began international operations by acquiring online sellers of books in the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In the subsequent year, it initiated the sale of a diverse range of products, including music, video games, consumer electronics, home improvement items, software, games, and toys.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2002, the company launched Amazon Web Services (AWS), which initially focused on providing APIs for web developers to build web applications on top of Amazon's e-commerce platform.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2004, AWS was expanded to provide website popularity statistics and web crawler data from the Alexa Web Information Service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] AWS later shifted toward providing enterprise services with Simple Storage Service (S3) in 2006, and Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) in 2008, allowing companies to rent data storage and computing power from Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2006, Amazon launched the*Fulfillment by Amazon*program, which allowed individuals and small companies (called "third-party sellers") to sell products through Amazon's warehouses and fulfillment infrastructure.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon purchased the Whole Foods Market supermarket chain in 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is the leading e-retailer in the United States with approximately US$178 billion net sales in 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It has over 300 million active customer accounts globally.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon saw large growth during the COVID-19 pandemic, hiring more than 100,000 staff in the United States and Canada.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Some Amazon workers in the US, France, and Italy protested the company's decision to "run normal shifts" due to COVID-19's ease of spread in warehouses.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In Spain, the company faced legal complaints over its policies, while a group of US Senators wrote an open letter to Bezos expressing concerns about workplace safety.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On February 2, 2021, Bezos announced that he would step down as CEO to become executive chair of Amazon's board.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The transition officially took place on July 5, 2021, with former CEO of AWS Andy Jassy replacing him as CEO.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2023, Amazon cut over 18,000 jobs, primarily in consumer retail and its human resources division in an attempt to cut costs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On November 8, 2023, a plan was adopted for Jeff Bezos to sell approximately 50 million shares of the company over the next year with a deadline of January 31, 2025.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The first step was the sale of 12 million shares for about $2 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On February 26, 2024, Amazon became a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On December 19, 2024, Amazon workers, led by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters labor union, went on strike against Amazon in at least four US states, with workers in other facilities in the United States being welcomed to join the strike as well.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On October 28, 2025, the company announced plans to reduce its corporate workforce by 14,000 positions, which has been reported as the largest round of job cuts by Amazon since 2022.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As part of this plan, Amazon is expected to fire about 370 people from its European headquarters in Luxembourg in December 2025 to early 2026.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced a second round of large-scale layoffs, affecting approximately 16,000 corporate employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] This followed the earlier reduction of 14,000 positions in October 2025.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] According to company statements and news reports, the layoffs were part of a broader effort to streamline operations, reduce bureaucracy, and adapt to changing business conditions, including the adoption of artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Affected employees were offered severance packages and support for internal job placement.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2025, Amazon filed an objection to Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing plan.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon invested $475 million into Saks’ acquisition of Neiman Marcus, and is now worried that Saks declaring bankruptcy would harm creditors and push the tech company further down the repayment pecking order.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2026, Amazon entered talks with OpenAI to invest up to $50 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon historically has a deep strategic partnership with Anthropic, OpenAI's competitor.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2026, Amazon also laid off 16,000 employees in what is Amazon's second round of large-scale job reductions in three months due to AI.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In February 2026, Amazon said it expected to invest $12 billion in Louisiana as part of a plan to build data centers there.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] This plan will create 540 full-time jobs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In March 2026, Amazon signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon launched Amazon Supply Chain Services in May 2026.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon websites are country-specific (for example, amazon.com for the US and amazon.co.uk for UK) though some offer international shipping.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Visits to *amazon.com* grew from 615 million annual visitors in 2008, to more than 2 billion per month in 2022.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The e-commerce platform is the 12th most visited website in the world.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In February 2024, Amazon announced its first chatbot, "Rufus", for use in the US; in July it was widely available to all customers in the US.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] "Rufus" is now available in the US, India and the UK which helps the shoppers get product recommendations, get shopping list advice, compare products and see what other customers have responded to regarding their specific questions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Results generated by Amazon's search engine are partly determined by promotional fees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2004, Toys "R" Us sued Amazon, claiming that because of a perceived lack of variety in Toys "R" Us stock, Amazon had knowingly allowed third-party sellers to offer items on the service in categories that Toys "R" Us had been granted exclusivity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2006, a court ruled in favor of Toys "R" Us, giving it the right to unwind its agreement with Amazon and establish its independent e-commerce website.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The company was later awarded $51 million in damages.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2001, Amazon entered into a similar agreement with Borders, under which Amazon would comanage Borders.com as a co-branded service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Borders pulled out of the arrangement in 2007, with plans to also launch its own online store.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On October 18, 2011, Amazon.com announced a partnership with DC Comics for the exclusive digital rights to many popular comics, including *Superman*, *Batman*, *Green Lantern*, *Sandman*, and *Watchmen*.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The partnership has caused well-known bookstores like Barnes & Noble to remove these titles from its shelves.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In November 2013, Amazon announced a partnership with the United States Postal Service to begin delivering orders on Sundays.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The service, included in Amazon's standard shipping rates, initiated in metropolitan areas of Greater Los Angeles and New York because of the high-volume and inability to deliver in a timely way, with plans to expand into Dallas, Houston, New Orleans and Phoenix by 2014.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In June 2017, Nike agreed to sell products through Amazon in exchange for better policing of counterfeit goods.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] This proved unsuccessful and Nike withdrew from the partnership in November 2019.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Companies including IKEA and Birkenstock also stopped selling through Amazon around the same time, citing similar frustrations over business practices and counterfeit goods.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In September 2017, Amazon ventured with one of its sellers JV Appario Retail owned by Patni Group which has recorded a total income of US$104.44 million (₹759 crore) in financial year 2017–2018.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of October 11, 2017, Amazon Fresh sold a range of Booths branded products for home delivery in selected areas.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In November 2018, Amazon reached an agreement with Apple Inc. to sell selected products through the service, via the company and selected Apple Authorized Resellers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As a result of this partnership, only Apple Authorized Resellers may sell Apple products on Amazon effective January 4, 2019.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On November 7, 2024, Amazon is reportedly discussing a second multi-billion dollar investment in AI startup Anthropic, following its initial $4 billion investment.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On 8 October 2025, Amazon launched prescription vending machines at One Medical clinics in Los Angeles.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The machines are operated by Amazon Pharmacy and are able to prescribe a range of common medications, such as antibiotics, inhalers and blood pressure treatments.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon sells many products under its own brand names, including phone chargers, batteries, and diaper wipes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The AmazonBasics brand was introduced in 2009, and now features hundreds of product lines, including smartphone cases, computer mice, batteries, dumbbells, and dog crates.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon owned 34 private-label brands as of 2019.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] These brands account for 0.15% of Amazon's global sales, whereas the average for other large retailers is 18%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Other Amazon retail brands include Presto!, Mama Bear, and Amazon Essentials.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon derives many of its sales (around 40% in 2008) from third-party sellers who sell products on Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Some other large e-commerce sellers use Amazon to sell their products in addition to selling them through their websites.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The sales are processed through Amazon.com and end up at individual sellers for processing and order fulfillment and Amazon leases space for these retailers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Small sellers of used and new goods go to Amazon Marketplace to offer goods at a fixed price.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Publishers can sign up as affiliates and receive a commission for referring customers to Amazon by placing links to Amazon on their websites if the referral results in a sale.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Worldwide, Amazon has "over 900,000 members" in its affiliate programs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of mid-2014, the Amazon Affiliate Program was used by 1.2% of all websites and was the second most popular advertising network after Google Ads.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is frequently used by websites and non-profits to provide a way for supporters to earn them a commission.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Associates can access the Amazon catalog directly on their websites by using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) XML service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] A new affiliate product, aStore, allows Associates to embed a subset of Amazon products within another website, or linked to another website.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In June 2010, Amazon Seller Product Suggestions was launched to provide more transparency to sellers by recommending specific products to third-party sellers to sell on Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Products suggested are based on customers' browsing history.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] A link -- embedded in a book name in an online article in *The New Yorker* and prefixed *cna.st/affiliate-link/* (the magazine is owned by Condé Nast) -- automatically redirected when accessed to the appropriate *amazon.com* page for the book.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon allows users to submit reviews to the web page of each product.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Reviewers must rate the product on a rating scale from one to five stars.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon provides a badging option for reviewers that indicates the real name of the reviewer (based on confirmation of a credit card account) or that indicates that the reviewer is one of the top reviewers by popularity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of 16 December 2020, Amazon removed the ability of sellers and customers to comment on product reviews and purged their websites of all posted product review comments.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In an email to sellers, Amazon gave its rationale for removing this feature: "...the comments feature on customer reviews was rarely used." The remaining review response options are to indicate whether the reader finds the review helpful or to report that it violates Amazon policies (abuse).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] If a review is given enough "helpful" hits, it appears on the front page of the product.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2010, Amazon was reported as being the largest single source of Internet consumer reviews.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] When publishers asked Bezos why Amazon would publish negative reviews, he defended the practice by claiming that Amazon.com was "taking a different approach...we want to make every book available—the good, the bad and the ugly...to let truth loose".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] There have been cases of positive reviews being written and posted by public relations companies on behalf of their clients and instances of writers using pseudonyms to leave negative reviews of their rivals' works.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The Amazon sales rank (ASR) indicates the popularity of a product sold on any Amazon locale.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is a relative indicator of popularity that is updated hourly.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Effectively, it is a "best sellers list" for the millions of products stocked by Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] While the ASR has no direct effect on the sales of a product, it is used by Amazon to determine which products to include in its bestsellers lists.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Products that appear in these lists enjoy additional exposure on the Amazon website and this may lead to an increase in sales.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In particular, products that experience large jumps (up or down) in their sales ranks may be included within Amazon's lists of "movers and shakers"; such a listing provides additional exposure that might lead to an increase in sales.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] For competitive reasons, Amazon does not release actual sales figures to the public.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] However, Amazon has now begun to release point of sale data via the BookScan service to verified authors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] While the ASR has been the source of much speculation by publishers, manufacturers, and marketers, Amazon itself does not release the details of its sales rank calculation algorithm.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In November 2015, Amazon opened a physical Amazon Books store in University Village in Seattle.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The store was 5,500 square feet and prices for all products matched those on its website.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon opened its tenth physical bookstore in 2017; media speculation at the time suggested that Amazon planned to eventually roll out 300 to 400 bookstores around the country.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] All of its locations were closed in 2022 along with other retail locations under the "Amazon 4-Star" brand.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In July 2016, the company announced that it was opening a 1,100,000 ft (335,280.0 m) square foot facility in Palmer Township in the Lehigh Valley region of eastern Pennsylvania.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of 2024, Amazon is the Lehigh Valley region's third-largest employer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In August 2019, Amazon applied to have a liquor store in San Francisco, as a means to ship beer and alcohol within the city.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2020, Amazon Fresh opened several physical stores in the US and the United Kingdom.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced it would close all of its Amazon Go and Amazon Fresh stores to shift focus to its online same-day delivery service and expand its Whole Foods Market business.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The closure affects 57 Fresh stores and 15 Amazon Go locations, some of which will be converted into Whole Foods stores.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon has a number of products and services available, including its digital assistant Alexa, Amazon Music, and Prime Video for music and videos respectively, the Amazon Appstore for Android apps, the Kindle line of electronic paper e-readers, Fire and Fire HD color LCD tablets.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Audible provides audiobooks for purchase and listening.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In September 2021, Amazon announced the launch of Astro, its first household robot, powered by its Alexa smart home technology.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] This can be remote-controlled when not at home, to check on pets, people, or home security.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It will send owners a notification if it detects something unusual.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In January 2023, Amazon announced the launch of RXPass, a prescription drug delivery service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon Prime members to pay a $5 monthly fee for access to 60 medications.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The service was launched immediately after the announcement except in states with specific prescription delivery requirements.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Beneficiaries of government healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid will not be able to sign up for RXPass.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon owns over 100 subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services, Audible, Diapers.com, Goodreads, IMDb, Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics), One Medical, Shopbop, Teachstreet, Twitch, Zappos, and Zoox.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Bezos separately owns *The Washington Post* (through Nash Holdings, LLC), Blue Origin, Bezos Expeditions, Altos Labs, and other companies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon Live is a video e-commerce live-streaming service created to compete with live-streaming services.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The service allows users to stream live videos promoting or sponsoring products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Users (mainly celebrities or Internet influencers) have the option to livestream on Amazon and add tags to additionally add context to the products they're selling or promoting.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Other users can join in and type in messages to send to a global chat on the livestream.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2019 Amazon launched an integrated platform into the Amazon website and application.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In 2023 roughly a billion total viewers watch Amazon Live across the United States and India.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The platform has also been integrated into Amazon Freevee and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a subsidiary of Amazon that provides on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs to individuals, companies, and governments, on a metered pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] These cloud computing web services provide distributed computing processing capacity and software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of 2021 Q4, AWS has 33% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 21%, and 10% respectively, according to Synergy Group.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Audible is a seller and producer of spoken audio entertainment, information, and educational programming on the Internet.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Audible sells digital audiobooks, radio and television programs, and audio versions of magazines and newspapers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Through its production arm, Audible Studios, Audible has also become the world's largest producer of downloadable audiobooks.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On January 31, 2008, Amazon announced it would buy Audible for about $300 million.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The deal closed in March 2008 and Audible became a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Goodreads is a "social cataloging" website founded in December 2006 and launched in January 2007 by Otis Chandler, a software engineer, and entrepreneur, and Elizabeth Khuri.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The website allows individuals to freely search Goodreads' extensive user-populated database of books, annotations, and reviews.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalogs and reading lists.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] They can also create their groups of book suggestions and discussions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In December 2007, the site had over 650,000 members, and over a million books had been added.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon bought the company in March 2013.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Ring is a home automation company founded by Jamie Siminoff in 2013.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is primarily known for its Wi-Fi powered smart doorbells, but manufactures other devices such as security cameras.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon bought Ring for US$1 billion in 2018.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Twitch is a live streaming platform for video, primarily oriented towards video gaming content.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Twitch was acquired by Amazon in August 2014 for $970 million.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The site's rapid growth had been boosted primarily by the prominence of major esports competitions on the service, leading *GameSpot* senior esports editor Rod Breslau to have described the service as "the ESPN of esports".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of 2015, the service had over 1.5 million broadcasters and 100 million monthly viewers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Whole Foods Market is an American supermarket chain exclusively featuring foods without artificial preservatives, colors, flavors, sweeteners, and hydrogenated fats.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon acquired Whole Foods for $13.7 billion in August 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Since acquiring Whole Foods, the company has launched its own chain of Fresh supermarkets and taken steps to integrate its online and physical grocery operations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon also has investments in renewable energy, including plans to fund four small nuclear reactors at the Xe-100 reactor site in Eastern Washington, and plans to expand its position into the Canadian market through an investment in a new plant in Alberta.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon's global headquarters are in more than 40 owned and leased buildings spread across Seattle's adjacent South Lake Union, Denny Triangle, and Downtown neighborhoods.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The first 14 buildings Amazon occupied in South Lake Union were developed primarily by Vulcan, Inc. from 2008 onward, the first 11 of which were acquired from Vulcan in 2012 at a cost of $1.16 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The company was previously headquartered in rented space within the Pacific Medical Center, located in the city's Beacon Hill neighborhood, from 1998 to 2011.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon is currently building a new four tower, four low-rise, complex in Seattle's Denny Triangle neighborhood to serve as the primary headquarters, though it will retain many of the earlier purchased buildings to house its more than 45,000 corporate employees in the Seattle area.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The plan for the new campus, designed by NBBJ and named "Rufus 2.0" after a dog who was a fixture of the company in its early days, was approved by the city of Seattle in 2012 and construction began the year after.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The first of the towers, nicknamed Doppler, opened on December 14, 2015.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon's European headquarters are in Luxembourg's capital, Luxembourg.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Its UK headquarters are at Principal Place, Shoreditch, London.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On November 13, 2018, Amazon announced that it would divide the planned HQ2 between New York City and Northern Virginia.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On February 14, 2019, Amazon canceled its plan for the HQ2 location in New York City.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon is also in the process of building a retail hub of operations center in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On August 21, 2019, Amazon opened its largest campus in the world at Nanakramguda in Hyderabad, India.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] It is the first Amazon-owned campus located outside the United States and features the single largest Amazon-owned building in the world.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The 9.5-acre campus houses over 15,000 employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon plans to build a major campus in Bellevue, Washington, a suburb of Seattle, that will host 15,000 employees by 2025.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The company opened its first Bellevue office in 2017, marking a return to the city since the company was founded there in 1995.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon's largest building in the city is Sonic, a 42-story building developed by Vulcan Real Estate with 1 million square feet (93,000 m2) of office space.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The Bellevue campus will include the 43-story Bellevue 600 tower, which is planned to be the tallest building in the city and the tallest to be developed by Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] While much of Amazon's software development occurs in Seattle, the company employs software developers in centers across the globe.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Some of these sites are run by an Amazon subsidiary called A2Z Development.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon has operated various retail store brands.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Most of the stores are located inside of the United States, but Whole Foods also operates stores in Canada and the United Kingdom, while Amazon Go has six locations in London under the Amazon Fresh name.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon uses many different transportation services to deliver packages.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon directly employs people to work at its warehouses, bulk distribution centers, staffed "Amazon Hub Locker+" locations, and delivery stations where drivers pick up packages.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] As of December 2020, it is not hiring delivery drivers as employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Rakuten Intelligence estimated that in 2020 in the United States, the proportion of last-mile deliveries was 56% by Amazon's directly contracted services (mostly in urban areas), 30% by the United States Postal Service (mostly in rural areas), and 14% by UPS.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In April 2021, Amazon reported to investors it had increased its in-house delivery capacity by 50% in the last 12 months (which included the first year of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In addition to Amazon Lockers, Amazon has around 30 staffed pickup points in the United States and over 800 independent ones in India.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The US locations have large sets of Amazon Lockers and an area for customers to make returns.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The India locations are in existing retailers and have customers wait for a store employee to retrieve their package.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon first launched its distribution network in 1997 with two fulfillment centers in Seattle and New Castle, Delaware.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon has several types of distribution facilities consisting of cross-dock centers, fulfillment centers, sortation centers, delivery stations, Prime now hubs, and Prime air hubs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] There are 75 fulfillment centers and 25 sortation centers with over 125,000 employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Employees are responsible for five basic tasks: unpacking and inspecting incoming goods; placing goods in storage and recording their location; picking goods from their computer recorded locations to make up an individual shipment; sorting and packing orders; and shipping.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] A computer that records the location of goods and maps out routes for pickers plays a key role: employees carry hand-held computers which communicate with the central computer and monitor their rate of progress.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Some warehouses are partially automated with systems built by Amazon Robotics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In September 2006, Amazon launched a program called FBA (Fulfillment By Amazon) whereby it could handle storage, packing and distribution of products and services for small sellers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers are large facilities with hundreds of employees, sometimes thousands.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] A picker may walk 10 or more miles a day.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In newer fulfillment centers, items are stored on pods and brought to pickers by robots (Amazon Robotics).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In the United Kingdom, initial staffing was provided by Randstad NV and other temporary employment agencies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In the United States, many workers are hired as Amazon employees and granted shares of stock or sign-on bonuses, while others are offered temporary seasonal positions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] "When we have permanent positions available, we look to the top-performing temporary associates to fill them," said an Amazon spokesperson.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon acquired Kiva Systems, a warehouse automation company, in 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers can also provide warehousing and order-fulfillment for third-party sellers, for an extra fee.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] Third-party sellers can use Fulfillment by Amazon (FBA) to ship for other platforms as well, such as eBay or their own websites.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] On March 20, 2020, Amazon agreed to remove metal detectors from its warehouses after a warehouse worker tested positive for COVID-19.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] In addition to removing metal detectors, Amazon enacted a "6 feet rule", which enforced a six-feet distance between warehouse employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p01] The Federal Public Health Emergency (PHE) for COVID-19 (which included social distancing) declared under Section 319 of the Public Health Service (PHS) Act, expired at the end of the day on May 11, 2023.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon.com is primarily a retail site with a sales revenue model; Amazon takes a small percentage of the sale price of each item that is sold through its website while also allowing companies to advertise their products by paying to be listed as featured products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] As of 2018, Amazon.com is ranked eighth on the Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In Forbes Global 2000 2023 Amazon ranked 36th.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] For the fiscal year 2021, Amazon reported earnings of US$33.36 billion, with an annual revenue of US$469.82 billion, an increase of 21.7% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Since 2007 sales increased from 14.835 billion to 469.822 billion, due to continued business expansion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon's market capitalization went over US$1 trillion again in early February 2020 after the announcement of the fourth quarter 2019 results.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] During his tenure, Jeff Bezos had become renowned for his annual shareholder letters, which have gained similar notability to those of Warren Buffett.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] These annual letters gave an "invaluable window" into the famously "secretive" company, and revealed Bezos's perspectives and strategic focus.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] A common theme of these letters is Bezos's desire to instill customer-centricity (in his words, "customer obsession") at all levels of Amazon, notably by making all senior executives field customer support queries for a short time at Amazon call centers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] He also read many emails addressed by customers to his public email address.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] One of Bezos's most well-known internal memos was his mandate for "all teams" to "expose their data and functionality" through service interfaces "designed from the ground up to be externalizable".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] This process, commonly known as a service-oriented architecture (SOA), resulted in mandatory dogfooding of services that would later be commercialized as part of AWS.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon has used internal recognition programs such as the Just Do It Award to encourage employee initiative and experimentation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon lobbies the United States federal government and state governments on multiple issues such as the enforcement of sales taxes on online sales, transportation safety, privacy and data protection and intellectual property.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] According to regulatory filings, Amazon.com focuses its lobbying on the United States Congress, the Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Reserve.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon.com spent roughly $3.5 million, $5 million and $9.5 million on lobbying, in 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In 2019, it spent $16.8 million and had a team of 104 lobbyists.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon.com was a corporate member of the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) until it dropped membership following protests at its shareholders' meeting on May 24, 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In 2014, Amazon expanded its lobbying practices as it prepared to lobby the Federal Aviation Administration to approve its drone delivery program, hiring the Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld lobbying firm in June.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon and its lobbyists have visited with Federal Aviation Administration officials and aviation committees in Washington, D.C. to explain its plans to deliver packages.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In September 2020 this moved one step closer with the granting of a critical certificate by the FAA.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] During the second Trump Administration, Amazon donated several times to various events and aspects of his presidency.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Along with several other major companies, Amazon donated $1 million to Trump's inaugural fund.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In April 2025, Amazon was a corporate sponsor of the White House Easter Egg Roll, after Donald Trump solicited corporate sponsors for the event for the first time.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In October 2025, Amazon was listed among the donors funding the construction of the White House State Ballroom.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon lobbies on climate policy internationally.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In the US, following Trump’s 2025 inauguration, Amazon began frequent engagements with the executive branch to advocate for permitting reform and energy development to support data center growth.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In July 2025, Amazon joined policymakers at the Pennsylvania Energy and Innovation Summit, where it supported the development of nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand, and lobbied for permitting reform to support grid development nationwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] A December 2025 DeSmog article reported that the company’s sponsorship came alongside several organizations that had supported climate change denial, and a continued role for fossil fuels to meet growing energy demand.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Criticism has also concerned various decisions over whether to censor or publish content such as the WikiLeaks website, works containing libel, anti-LGBT merchandise, and material facilitating dog fighting, cockfighting, or pedophile activities.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] An article published by *Time* in the wake of social media website Parler's termination of service by Amazon Web Service highlights the power companies like Amazon now have over the internet.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In December 2011, Amazon faced a backlash from small businesses for running a one-day deal to promote its new Price Check app.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Shoppers who used the app to check prices in a brick-and-mortar store were offered a 5% discount to purchase the same item from Amazon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Companies like Groupon, eBay and Taap have countered Amazon's promotion by offering $10 off from its products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] The company has also faced accusations of putting undue pressure on suppliers to maintain and extend its profitability.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In 2019, Amazon banned selling skin-lightening products after pushback from Minnesota health and environmental activists.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In 2022, a lawsuit filed by state attorney-general Letitia James was dismissed by the New York state court of appeals.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] After the COVID-19 pandemic, Amazon faced criticism for complying, under pressure from the Biden Administration, to "reduce the visibility" of books critical of the COVID-19 vaccine, which was revealed after Rep.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Jim Jordan (acting on behalf of the House Judiciary Committee) subpoenaed emails between the company and the Biden Administration.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Amazon Prime has been criticized for its vehicles systemically double parking, blocking bike lanes, and otherwise violating traffic laws while dropping off packages, contributing to traffic congestion and endangering other road users.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Jane Friedman discovered six listings of books fraudulently using her name, on Amazon and Goodreads.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In 2024, following years of criticism for providing law enforcement footage in the custody of Ring (a home security company owned by Amazon) without a warrant, Ring has halted this practice.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] It received cautious praise from privacy-focused organizations such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation for this change.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In February 2025, Sky accused Amazon of not doing enough to prevent the piracy of its sports rights via "jailbroken" Fire Sticks.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Project Nimbus is a contract by which Amazon and Google provide Israel and its military with artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other cloud-computing services.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] The contract has been criticized by shareholders and employees concerned that the project may lead to abuses of Palestinian human rights in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In October 2025, Amazon suspended an employee who posted messages to the company's Slack and wrote a letter to Andy Jassy criticizing Nimbus.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] On July 22, 2025, Amazon announced its plan to acquire San Francisco-based startup Bee AI.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] Bee produces a wristband, similar to most modern smartwatches, equipped with AI and microphones.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] The wristband is capable of providing summaries of conversations and reminders of tasks, effectively serving as a 24/7 note taker.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] News outlets criticize the fact that the devices saves transcripts, potentially utilizing it to train generative AI models which require vast quantities of data.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] In January 2026, Amazon sent a notice out to cloud staffers in an apparent error acknowledging “organizational changes” at the company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/amazon-inc-p02] The note also mentioned a "Project Dawn" which was cancelled, although it is unclear what the project is about.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Organizations may apply analytics to business data to describe, predict, and improve business performance.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Specifically, areas within analytics include descriptive analytics, diagnostic analytics, predictive analytics, prescriptive analytics, and cognitive analytics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Analytics may apply to a variety of fields such as marketing, management, finance, online systems, information security, and software services.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Since analytics can require extensive computation (see big data), the algorithms and software used for analytics harness the most current methods in computer science, statistics, and mathematics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] According to International Data Corporation, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] As per Gartner, the overall analytic platforms software market grew by $25.5 billion in 2020.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Data analysis focuses on the process of examining past data through business understanding, data understanding, data preparation, modeling and evaluation, and deployment.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] It is a subset of data analytics, which takes multiple data analysis processes to focus on why an event happened and what may happen in the future based on the previous data.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Data analytics is used to formulate larger organizational decisions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Data analytics is a multidisciplinary field.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] There is extensive use of computer skills, mathematics, statistics, descriptive techniques, and predictive models to gain valuable knowledge from data through analytics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] It also includes unsupervised machine learning techniques like cluster analysis, principal component analysis, segmentation profile analysis, and association analysis.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Marketing organizations use analytics to evaluate the outcomes of campaigns and initiatives, as well as to guide decisions related to investment and consumer targeting.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Techniques such as demographic studies, customer segmentation, conjoint analysis, and others enable marketers to analyze large volumes of consumer purchase data, survey data, and panel data.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] This helps them better understand consumer behavior and effectively communicate marketing strategies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Marketing analytics consists of both qualitative and quantitative, structured and unstructured data used to drive strategic decisions about brand and revenue outcomes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The process involves predictive modelling, marketing experimentation, automation, and real-time sales communications.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The data enables companies to make predictions and alter strategic execution to maximize performance results.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Web analytics allows marketers to collect session-level information about interactions on a website using an operation called sessionization.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Google Analytics is an example of a popular free analytics tool that marketers use for this purpose.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Those interactions provide web analytics information systems with the information necessary to track the referrer, search keywords, identify the IP address, and track the activities of the visitor.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] With this information, a marketer can improve marketing campaigns, website creative content, and information architecture.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Analysis techniques frequently used in marketing include marketing mix modeling, pricing and promotion analyses, sales force optimization, and customer analytics, e.g., segmentation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Web analytics and optimization of websites and online campaigns now frequently work hand in hand with the more traditional marketing analysis techniques.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] A focus on digital media has slightly changed the vocabulary so that *marketing mix modeling* is commonly referred to as *attribution modeling* in the digital or marketing mix modeling context.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] People analytics uses behavioral data to understand how people work and change how companies are managed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] It can be referred to by various names, depending on the context, the purpose of the analytics, or the specific focus of the analysis.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Some examples include workforce analytics, HR analytics, talent analytics, people insights, talent insights, colleague insights, human capital analytics, and human resources information system (HRIS) analytics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] HR analytics is the application of analytics to help companies manage human resources.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] HR analytics has become a strategic tool in analyzing and forecasting human-related trends in the changing labor markets, using career analytics tools.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The aim is to discern which employees to hire, which to reward or promote, what responsibilities to assign, and similar human resource problems.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] For example, inspection of the strategic phenomenon of employee turnover utilizing people analytics tools may serve as an important analysis at times of disruption.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] It has been suggested that people analytics is a separate discipline to HR analytics, with a greater focus on addressing business issues, while HR Analytics is more concerned with metrics related to HR processes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Additionally, people analytics may now extend beyond the human resources function in organizations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] However, experts find that many HR departments are burdened by operational tasks and need to prioritize people analytics and automation to become a more strategic and capable business function in the evolving world of work, rather than producing basic reports that offer limited long-term value.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Some experts argue that a change in the way HR departments operate is essential.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Although HR functions were traditionally centered on administrative tasks, they are now evolving with a new generation of data-driven HR professionals who serve as strategic business partners.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Examples of HR analytic metrics include employee lifetime value (ELTV), labour cost expense percent, union percentage, etc.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] **Quality of promotion** is a metric used to assess a person's promotion decisions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The metric determines whether employees appropriately advanced on objective criteria rather or if a bias is present.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] A common application of business analytics is portfolio analysis.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] In this, a bank or lending agency has a collection of accounts of varying value and risk.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The accounts may differ by the social status (wealthy, middle-class, poor, etc.) of the holder, the geographical location, its net value, and many other factors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The lender must balance the return on the loan with the risk of default for each loan.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The question is then how to evaluate the portfolio as a whole.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The least risk loan may be to the very wealthy, but there are a very limited number of wealthy people.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] On the other hand, there are many poor that can be lent to, but at greater risk.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Some balance must be struck that maximizes return and minimizes risk.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The analytics solution may combine time series analysis with many other issues in order to make decisions on when to lend money to these different borrower segments, or decisions on the interest rate charged to members of a portfolio segment to cover any losses among members in that segment.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Predictive models in the banking industry are developed to bring certainty across the risk scores for individual customers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Credit scores are built to predict an individual's delinquency behavior and are widely used to evaluate the credit worthiness of each applicant.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Furthermore, risk analyses are carried out in the scientific world and the insurance industry.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] It is also extensively used in financial institutions like online payment gateway companies to analyse if a transaction was genuine or fraud.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] For this purpose, they use the transaction history of the customer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] This is more commonly used in Credit Card purchases, when there is a sudden spike in the customer transaction volume the customer gets a call of confirmation if the transaction was initiated by him/her.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] This helps in reducing loss due to such circumstances.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Digital analytics is a set of business and technical activities that define, create, collect, verify, or transform digital data into reporting, research, analyses, recommendations, optimizations, predictions, and automation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] This also includes SEO (search engine optimization), where the keyword search is tracked and that data is used for marketing purposes, and banner ad clicks.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] A growing number of brands and marketing firms rely on digital analytics for their digital marketing assignments, where marketing return on investment (MROI) is an important key performance indicator (KPI).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Security analytics refers to information technology (IT) to gather security events to understand and analyze events that pose the greatest security risks.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Products in this area include security information and event management and user behavior analytics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Software analytics is the process of collecting information about the way a piece of software is used and produced.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] In the industry of commercial analytics software, an emphasis has emerged on solving the challenges of analyzing massive, complex data sets, often when such data is in a constant state of change.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Such data sets are commonly referred to as big data.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Whereas once the problems posed by big data were only found in the scientific community, today big data is a problem for many businesses that operate transactional systems online and, as a result, amass large volumes of data quickly.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] The analysis of unstructured data types is another challenge getting attention in the industry.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Unstructured data differs from structured data in that its format varies widely and cannot be stored in traditional relational databases without significant effort at data transformation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Sources of unstructured data, such as email, the contents of word processor documents, PDFs, geospatial data, etc., are rapidly becoming a relevant source of business intelligence for businesses, governments, and universities.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] These challenges are the current inspiration for much of the innovation in modern analytics information systems, giving birth to relatively new machine analysis concepts such as complex event processing, full text search and analysis, and even new ideas in presentation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] One such innovation is the introduction of grid-like architecture in machine analysis, allowing increases in the speed of massively parallel processing by distributing the workload to many computers all with equal access to the complete data set.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Analytics is increasingly used in education, particularly at the district and government office levels.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] However, the complexity of student performance measures presents challenges when educators try to understand and use analytics to discern patterns in student performance, predict graduation likelihood, improve chances of student success, etc.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] For example, in a study involving districts known for strong data use, 48% of teachers had difficulty posing questions prompted by data, 36% did not comprehend given data, and 52% incorrectly interpreted data.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] To combat this, some analytics tools for educators adhere to an over-the-counter data format (embedding labels, supplemental documentation, and a help system, and making key package/display and content decisions) to improve educators' understanding and use of the analytics being displayed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/analytics] Risks for the general population include discrimination on the basis of characteristics such as gender, skin colour, ethnic origin, or political opinions through mechanisms such as price discrimination or statistical discrimination.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company was founded to market Wozniak's Apple I personal computer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Its successor, the Apple II, became one of the first successful mass-produced microcomputers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple introduced the Lisa in 1983 and the Macintosh in 1984 as some of the first computers to use a graphical user interface and a mouse.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] By 1985, internal conflicts led to Jobs leaving the company to form NeXT and Wozniak withdrawing to other ventures; John Sculley was CEO for over a decade.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In the 1990s, Apple lost considerable market share in the PC industry to the lower-priced Wintel duopoly of Intel-powered PC clones running Windows, and was reporting major losses by 1997.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] To overhaul its market strategy, Apple acquired NeXT, bringing Jobs back to the company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Under his leadership, Apple returned to profitability by introducing the iMac, iPod, iPhone, and iPad devices; creating the iTunes Store; launching the "Think different" advertising campaign; and opening the Apple Store retail chain.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs resigned in 2011 for health reasons and died the same year.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] He was succeeded as CEO by Tim Cook, who will be succeeded by John Ternus in September 2026.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Since 2011, Apple has for the most part been the world's largest company by market capitalization, and, as of 2024, is the largest manufacturing company by revenue, the fourth-largest PC vendor, the largest vendor of tablet computers, and the largest vendor of mobile phones.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple became the first publicly traded US company to be valued at over $1 trillion in 2018, and, as of October 2025, is valued at just over $4 trillion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple has received criticism regarding its contractors' labor conditions, its relationship with trade unions, its environmental practices, and its corporate ethics, including anti-competitive tactics, materials sourcing, and its acquisitions of smaller businesses.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Nevertheless, the company has a large following and enjoys a high level of customer loyalty.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple has consistently been ranked as one of the world's most valuable brands since the late 2000s.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple Computer Company was founded on April 1, 1976, by Steve Jobs, Steve Wozniak, and Ronald Wayne as a partnership.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company's first product was the Apple I, a computer designed and hand-built entirely by Wozniak.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] To finance its creation, Jobs sold his Volkswagen Bus, and Wozniak sold his HP-65 calculator.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Neither received the full selling price, but together they earned $1,300 (equivalent to $7,400 in 2025).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak debuted the first prototype Apple I at the Homebrew Computer Club in July 1976.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Apple I was sold as a motherboard with CPU, RAM, and basic textual-video chips—a base kit concept which was not yet marketed as a complete personal computer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak later said he was unaware of the coincidental mark of the beast in the number 666, and that he came up with the price because he liked "repeating digits".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple Computer, Inc. was incorporated in Cupertino, California, on January 3, 1977, without Wayne, who had left and sold his share of the company back to Jobs and Wozniak for $800 only twelve days after having co-founded it.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Multimillionaire Mike Markkula provided essential business expertise and funding of $250,000 (equivalent to $1,328,000 in 2025) to Jobs and Wozniak during the incorporation of Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During the first five years of operations, revenue grew exponentially, doubling about every four months.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Between September 1977 and September 1980, yearly sales grew from $775,000 to US$118 million, an average annual growth rate of 533%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Apple II, also designed by Wozniak, was introduced on April 16, 1977, at the first West Coast Computer Faire.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It differed from its major rivals, the TRS-80 and Commodore PET, because of its character cell-based color graphics and open architecture.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Apple I and early Apple II models used ordinary audio cassette tapes as storage devices, which were superseded by the 5+1⁄4-inch floppy disk drive and interface called the Disk II in 1978.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Apple II was chosen to be the desktop platform for the first killer application of the business world: VisiCalc, a spreadsheet program released in 1979.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] VisiCalc created a business market for the Apple II and gave home users an additional reason to buy an Apple II: compatibility with the office, but Apple II market share remained behind home computers made by competitors such as Atari, Commodore, and Tandy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] By the end of the day, around 300 millionaires were created, including Jobs and Wozniak, from a stock price of $29 per share and a market cap of $1.778 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In November and December 1979, Steve Jobs and Apple employees, including Jef Raskin, visited Xerox PARC, where they observed the Xerox Alto, featuring a graphical user interface (GUI) and a mouse.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs had negotiated with Xerox in advance to gain access to PARC's technology, in exchange for the right to purchase $1 million worth of Apple's pre-IPO shares.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This visit influenced Jobs to implement a GUI in Apple's products starting with the Apple Lisa in 1983, though he was forced out of the Lisa project during the early development.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Despite being pioneering as a mass-marketed GUI computer, the Lisa suffered from high costs and limited software options, leading to commercial failure.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Following his removal from the Lisa team, Jobs joined the company's Macintosh division in January 1981.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Macintosh had been envisioned by Jef Raskin as a low-cost, portable computer, and Wozniak had helped its development until a plane crash in early 1981 forced him to step back from the project.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak's absence allowed Jobs to take over the project and he redefined the Macintosh as a mouse-driven GUI machine similar to the Lisa.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak speculates that Jobs' sense of rivalry towards the Lisa project was the driving force behind this sudden shift in direction.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs was also hostile to the Apple II division, which at the time generated most of the company's revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 1984, Apple launched the Macintosh, the first personal computer without a bundled programming language.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Its debut was signified by "1984", a US$1.5-million television advertisement directed by Ridley Scott that aired during the third quarter of Super Bowl XVIII on January 22, 1984.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This was hailed as a watershed event for Apple's success and was called a "masterpiece" by CNN and one of the greatest TV advertisements of all time by *TV Guide*.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The advertisement created great interest in the Macintosh, and sales were initially good, but began to taper off dramatically after the first three months as reviews started coming in.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs had required 128 kilobytes of RAM, which limited its speed and software in favor of aspiring for a projected price point of $1,000 (equivalent to $3,100 in 2025).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Macintosh shipped for $2,495 (equivalent to $7,700 in 2025), a price panned by critics due to its slow performance.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The board of directors instructed Sculley to contain Jobs and his ability to launch expensive forays into untested products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Rather than submit to Sculley's direction, Jobs attempted to oust him from leadership.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jean-Louis Gassée informed Sculley that Jobs had been attempting to organize a boardroom coup, and called an emergency meeting at which Apple's executive staff sided with Sculley, and stripped Jobs of all operational duties.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs resigned from Apple in September 1985 and took several Apple employees with him to found NeXT.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak had also quit his active employment at Apple earlier in 1985 to pursue other ventures, expressing his frustration with Apple's treatment of the Apple II division and stating that the company had "been going in the wrong direction for the last five years".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Wozniak remained employed by Apple as a representative, receiving a stipend estimated to be $120,000 per year.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs and Wozniak remained Apple shareholders following their departures.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] After the departures of Jobs and Wozniak in 1985, Sculley launched the Macintosh 512K that year with quadruple the RAM, and introduced the LaserWriter, the first reasonably priced PostScript-based laser printer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] PageMaker, an early desktop publishing application taking advantage of the PostScript language, was also released by Aldus Corporation in July 1985.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It has been suggested that the combination of Macintosh, LaserWriter, and PageMaker was responsible for the creation of the desktop publishing market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This dominant position in the desktop publishing market allowed the company to focus on higher price points, the so-called "high-right policy" named for its position on a price–profits chart.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Newer models selling at higher price points offered higher profit margin, and appeared to not affect total sales as power users snapped up every increase in speed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Although some worried about pricing themselves out of the market, the high-right policy was in full force by the mid-1980s, due to Jean-Louis Gassée's slogan of "fifty-five or die", referring to the 55% profit margins of the Macintosh II.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This policy began to backfire late in the decade as desktop publishing programs appeared on IBM PC compatibles with some of the same functionality of the Macintosh at far lower price points.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company lost its dominant position in the desktop publishing market and estranged many of its original consumer customer base, who could no longer afford Apple products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Christmas season of 1989 was the first in the company's history to have declining sales, which led to a 20% drop in Apple's stock price.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During this period, the relationship between Sculley and Gassée deteriorated, leading Sculley to effectively demote Gassée in January 1990 by appointing Michael Spindler as the chief operating officer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Gassée left the company later that year to set up a rival, Be Inc.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company pivoted its strategy and, in October 1990, introduced three lower-cost models: the Macintosh Classic, the Macintosh LC, and the Macintosh IIsi, all of which generated strong sales.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 1991, Apple introduced the PowerBook, a commercially successful laptop whose clamshell design influenced later notebook computers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The same year, Apple introduced System 7, a major upgrade to the Macintosh operating system that introduced a color user interface and improved networking capabilities.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The success of the lower-cost Macintosh models and the PowerBook brought increasing revenue, and the period from 1989 to 1991 was later described by *MacAddict* as the "first golden age" of the Macintosh.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] However, the success of the lower-cost Macintosh models also cannibalized sales of Apple's higher-end systems.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In response, the company introduced several new brands, selling largely identical machines at different price points, for different markets: the high-end Quadra series, the mid-range Centris, and the consumer-oriented Performa.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This led to widespread consumer confusion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple discontinued the Apple II series in 1993 after encouraging developers and customers to transition to the Macintosh, bringing the company's longest-running product line to an end.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During the 1990s, Apple also introduced several consumer products, including the QuickTake digital cameras, PowerCD, the Pippin game console, eWorld, Apple Interactive Television Box, and the Newton tablet division.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Although technologically ambitious, they were commercially unsuccessful.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Meanwhile, Microsoft expanded the reach of Windows by focusing on inexpensive personal computers, while Apple continued to emphasize premium hardware with high profit margins.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple unsuccessfully sued Microsoft over similarities between Windows and the Lisa's operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The consumer product flops and the rapid loss of market share to Windows sullied Apple's reputation, and in 1993 Sculley was replaced as CEO by Michael Spindler.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 1994, Apple, IBM, and Motorola formed the AIM alliance to promote the PowerPC platform.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] That year, Apple introduced the first Power Macintosh models using PowerPC processors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In the wake of the alliance, Apple opened up to the idea of allowing Motorola and other companies to build Macintosh clones.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Over the next two years, 75 distinct Macintosh clone models were introduced.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] However, by 1996, Apple executives were worried that the clones were cannibalizing sales of its own high-end computers, where profit margins were highest.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 1996, Spindler was replaced as CEO by Gil Amelio, who was hired for his reputation as a corporate rehabilitator.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Amelio made big changes, including extensive layoffs and cost-cutting.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This period was also marked by repeated attempts to modernize the Macintosh operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The original System 1 was not built for multitasking (running several applications at once), and although Apple introduced cooperative multitasking in System 5, the company concluded that a more modern approach was needed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Internal efforts, including the Pink project, A/UX, and Copland, failed to produce a suitable successor.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple then sought to acquire an external operating system, first entering negotiations to purchase BeOS.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The talks collapsed when Be CEO and former Apple executive Jean-Louis Gassée demanded $300 million, well above Apple's $125 million offer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple instead acquired NeXT, the technology company founded by Apple co-founder Steve Jobs after his 1985 ouster from Apple, for its NeXTSTEP operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple would purchase the company for $427 million in cash, stock, stock options, and assumed debt.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] At the insistence of Amelio, Jobs accepted 1.5 million Apple shares as part of the deal rather than an all-cash payment, lending credibility to the acquisition.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Under the agreement, Jobs returned to Apple as an advisor.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The NeXT acquisition was completed on February 7, 1997.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs soon became frustrated with the leadership of Amelio and Apple's board, and in June 1997 anonymously sold his 1.5 million shares, sending the company's stock to a 12-year low.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The stock slide rattled the board, which ousted Amelio as CEO the following month.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs became Apple's *de facto* leader and was formally appointed interim CEO on September 16.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In August 1997, Jobs secured a $150 million investment from Microsoft and a commitment to continue developing software for the Mac platform, an agreement widely viewed as beneficial to both companies following Microsoft's antitrust settlement with the U.S.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs ended the Macintosh clone licensing program, and in September 1997, acquired the largest clone manufacturer, Power Computing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In November 1997, the online Apple Store launched and adopted a build-to-order manufacturing model similar to that used by Dell.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] By the end of 1997, Jobs had returned Apple to profitability, reporting a profit of $309 million.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs streamlined Apple's product lineup, eliminating roughly 70 percent of existing models and introducing a simplified 'four-quadrant' product strategy consisting of one desktop and one laptop computer each for consumer and professional markets.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The restructuring eliminated approximately 3,000 jobs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The first major product introduced under this strategy was the iMac, unveiled on May 6, 1998.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Designed by Jony Ive, the all-in-one computer featured a distinctive translucent design enclosure, emphasized Internet connectivity (the "i" in iMac), adopted modern technologies such as USB, and omitted legacy technologies like the floppy disk drive.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It sold approximately 800,000 units within its first five months on the market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple completed the transition to the four-quadrant lineup on July 21, 1999, with the introduction of the consumer-oriented iBook laptop.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It joined the iMac and refined versions of the existing professional Power Macintosh desktop and PowerBook laptop, completing the simplified product matrix.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs said the smaller product lineup allowed Apple to focus more on quality and innovation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Around then, Apple also completed numerous acquisitions to create a portfolio of digital media production software for both professionals and consumers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple acquired Macromedia's Key Grip digital video editing software project, which was launched as Final Cut Pro in April 1999.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Key Grip's development also led to Apple's release of the consumer video-editing product iMovie in October 1999.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple acquired the German company Astarte in April 2000, which had developed the DVD authoring software DVDirector, which Apple repackaged as the professional-oriented DVD Studio Pro, and reused its technology to create iDVD for the consumer market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2000, Apple purchased the SoundJam MP audio player software from Casady & Greene.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple renamed the program iTunes, simplified the user interface and added CD burning.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2001, Apple changed course with three announcements.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] First, on March 24, 2001, Apple announced the release of a new modern operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This was after numerous failed attempts in the early 1990s, and several years of development.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Mac OS X is based on NeXTSTEP, OpenStep, and BSD Unix, to combine the stability, reliability, and security of Unix with the ease of use of an overhauled user interface.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Second, in May 2001, the first two Apple Store retail locations opened in Virginia and California, offering an improved presentation of the company's products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] At the time, many speculated that the stores would fail, but they later expanded to more than 500 locations worldwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Third, on October 23, 2001, the iPod portable digital audio player debuted.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The product was first sold on November 10, 2001, and sold over 100 million units within six years.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2003, the iTunes Store was introduced with music downloads for 99¢ a song and iPod integration.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It quickly became the market leader in online music services, with over 5 billion downloads by June 19, 2008.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Two years later, the iTunes Store was the world's largest music retailer.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2002, Apple purchased Nothing Real for its advanced digital compositing application Shake, and Emagic for the music productivity application Logic.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The purchase of Emagic made Apple the first computer manufacturer to own a music software company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The acquisition was followed by the development of Apple's consumer-level GarageBand application.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The release of iPhoto that year completed the iLife suite.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] At the Worldwide Developers Conference keynote address on June 6, 2005, Jobs announced that Apple would move away from PowerPC processors, and the Mac would transition to Intel processors in 2006.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On January 10, 2006, the new MacBook Pro and iMac became the first Apple computers to use Intel's Core Duo CPU.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] By August 7, 2006, Apple made the transition to Intel chips for the entire Mac product line—over one year sooner than announced.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The Power Mac, iBook, and PowerBook brands were retired during the transition; the Mac Pro, MacBook, and MacBook Pro became their respective successors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also introduced Boot Camp in 2006 to help users install Windows XP or Windows Vista on their Intel Macs alongside Mac OS X.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Between early 2003 and 2006, the price of Apple's stock increased more than tenfold, from around $6 per share (split-adjusted) to over $80.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] When Apple surpassed Dell's market cap in January 2006, Jobs sent an email to Apple employees saying Dell's CEO Michael Dell should eat his words.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Nine years prior, Dell had said that if he ran Apple he would "shut it down and give the money back to the shareholders".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During his keynote speech at the Macworld Expo on January 9, 2007, Jobs announced the renaming of Apple Computer, Inc. to Apple Inc., because the company had broadened its focus from computers to consumer electronics.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This event also saw the announcement of the iPhone and the Apple TV.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company sold 270,000 first-generation iPhones during the first 30 hours of sales, and some industry commentators described the device as "a game changer for the industry".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In an article posted on Apple's website on February 6, 2007, Jobs wrote that Apple would be willing to sell music on the iTunes Store without digital rights management, thereby allowing tracks to be played on third-party players if record labels would agree to drop the technology.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On April 2, 2007, Apple and EMI jointly announced the removal of DRM technology from EMI's catalog in the iTunes Store, effective in May 2007.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Other record labels eventually followed suit and Apple published a press release in January 2009 to announce that all songs on the iTunes Store are available without its FairPlay DRM.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In July 2008, Apple launched the App Store to sell third-party applications for the iPhone and iPod Touch.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Within a month, the store sold 60 million applications and registered an average daily revenue of $1 million, with Jobs speculating in August 2008 that the App Store could become a billion-dollar business for Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] By October 2008, Apple was the third-largest mobile handset supplier in the world due to the popularity of the iPhone.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On January 14, 2009, Jobs announced in an internal memo that he would be taking a six-month medical leave of absence from Apple until the end of June 2009 and would spend the time focusing on his health.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In the email, Jobs stated that "the curiosity over my personal health continues to be a distraction not only for me and my family, but everyone else at Apple as well", and explained that the break would allow the company "to focus on delivering extraordinary products".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Though Jobs was absent, Apple recorded its best non-holiday quarter (Q1 FY 2009) during the recession, with revenue of $8.16 billion and profit of $1.21 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] After years of speculation and multiple rumored "leaks", Apple unveiled a large screen, tablet-like media device known as the iPad on January 27, 2010.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPad ran the same touch-based operating system as the iPhone, and all iPhone apps were compatible with the iPad.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This gave the iPad a large app catalog on launch, though having very little development time before the release.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Later that year on April 3, 2010, the iPad was launched in the US.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It sold more than 300,000 units on its first day, and 500,000 by the end of the first week.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In May 2010, Apple's market cap exceeded that of competitor Microsoft for the first time since 1989.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2010, Apple released the iPhone 4, which introduced video calling using FaceTime, multitasking, and a new design with an exposed stainless steel frame as the phone's antenna system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Later that year, Apple again refreshed the iPod line by introducing a multi-touch iPod Nano, an iPod Touch with FaceTime, and an iPod Shuffle that brought back the clickwheel buttons of earlier generations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It also introduced the smaller, cheaper second-generation Apple TV which allowed the rental of movies and shows.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On January 17, 2011, Jobs announced in an internal Apple memo that he would take another medical leave of absence for an indefinite period to allow him to focus on his health.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Chief operating officer Tim Cook assumed Jobs' day-to-day operations at Apple, although Jobs would still remain "involved in major strategic decisions".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple became the most valuable consumer-facing brand in the world, and has consistently been among the most valuable brands since then.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2011, Jobs took the stage and unveiled iCloud, an online storage and syncing service for music, photos, files, and software which replaced MobileMe, Apple's previous attempt at content syncing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This would be the last product launch Jobs would attend before his death.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On August 24, 2011, Jobs resigned his position as CEO of Apple due to his health issues.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] He was replaced by Cook and Jobs became Apple's chairman.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple did not have a chairman at the time and instead had two co-lead directors, Andrea Jung and Arthur D.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Levinson, who continued with those titles until Levinson replaced Jobs as chairman of the board in November after Jobs' death.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On October 5, 2011, Steve Jobs died, marking the end of an era for Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The next major product announcement by Apple was on January 19, 2012, when Apple's Phil Schiller introduced iBooks Textbooks for iOS and iBooks Author for Mac OS X in New York City.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Jobs stated in the biography *Steve Jobs* that he wanted to reinvent the textbook industry and education.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] These launches were successful, with the iPhone 5 (released September 21, 2012) becoming Apple's biggest iPhone launch with over two million pre-orders and sales of three million iPads in three days following the launch of the iPad Mini and fourth-generation iPad (released November 3, 2012).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also released a third-generation 13-inch MacBook Pro with a Retina display and new iMac and Mac Mini computers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On August 20, 2012, Apple's rising stock price increased the company's market capitalization to a then-record $624 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This beat the non-inflation-adjusted record for market capitalization previously set by Microsoft in 1999.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On August 24, 2012, a US jury ruled that Samsung should pay Apple $1.05 billion (£665m) in damages in an intellectual property lawsuit.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Samsung appealed the damages award, which was reduced by $450 million and further granted Samsung's request for a new trial.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On November 10, 2012, Apple confirmed a global settlement that dismissed all existing lawsuits between Apple and HTC up to that date, in favor of a ten-year license agreement for current and future patents between the two companies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It is predicted that Apple will make US$280 million per year from this deal with HTC.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In May 2014, Apple confirmed its intent to acquire Dr.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Dre and Jimmy Iovine's audio company Beats Electronics, producer of the "Beats by Dr.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Dre" line of headphones and speaker products, and operator of the music streaming service Beats Music, for US$3 billion, and to sell its products through Apple's retail outlets and resellers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Iovine believed that Beats had always "belonged" with Apple, as the company modeled itself after Apple's "unmatched ability to marry culture and technology".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The acquisition was the largest purchase in Apple's history.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During a press event on September 9, 2014, Apple introduced a smartwatch called the Apple Watch.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Initially, Apple marketed the device as a fashion accessory and a complement to the iPhone, that would allow people to look at their smartphones less.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Over time, the company has focused on developing health and fitness-oriented features on the watch, in an effort to compete with dedicated activity trackers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In January 2016, Apple announced that over one billion Apple devices were in active use worldwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On June 6, 2016, *Fortune* released the *Fortune* 500, its annual list of companies ranked on revenue generation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In the trailing fiscal year of 2015, Apple was listed as the top tech company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] It ranked third, overall, with US$233 billion in revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This represents a movement upward of two spots from the previous year's list.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2017, Apple announced the HomePod, its smart speaker aimed to compete against Sonos, Google Home, and Amazon Echo.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Toward the end of the year, *TechCrunch* reported that Apple was acquiring Shazam, a company that introduced its products at WWDC and specializing in music, TV, film and advertising recognition.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The acquisition was confirmed a few days later, reportedly costing Apple US$400 million, with media reports that the purchase looked like a move to acquire data and tools bolstering the Apple Music streaming service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The purchase was approved by the European Union in September 2018.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Also in June 2017, Apple appointed Jamie Erlicht and Zack Van Amburg to head the newly formed worldwide video unit.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In November 2017, Apple announced it was branching out into original scripted programming: a drama series starring Jennifer Aniston and Reese Witherspoon, and a reboot of the anthology series *Amazing Stories* with Steven Spielberg.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2018, Apple signed the Writers Guild of America's minimum basic agreement and Oprah Winfrey to a multi-year content partnership.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Additional partnerships for original series included Sesame Workshop and DHX Media and its subsidiary Peanuts Worldwide, and a partnership with A24 to create original films.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During the Apple Special Event in September 2017, the AirPower wireless charger was announced alongside the iPhone X, iPhone 8, and Watch Series 3.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The AirPower was intended to wirelessly charge multiple devices, simultaneously.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Though initially set to release in early 2018, the AirPower would be canceled in March 2019, marking the first cancellation of a device under Cook's leadership.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On August 19, 2020, Apple's share price briefly topped $467.77, making it the first US company with a market capitalization of US$2 trillion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] During its annual WWDC keynote speech on June 22, 2020, Apple announced it would move away from Intel processors, and the Mac would transition to processors developed in-house.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The announcement was expected by industry analysts, and it has been noted that Macs featuring Apple's processors would allow for big increases in performance over current Intel-based models.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On November 10, 2020, the MacBook Air, MacBook Pro, and the Mac Mini became the first Macs powered by an Apple-designed processor, the Apple M1.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In April 2022, it was reported that Samsung Electro-Mechanics would be collaborating with Apple on its M2 chip instead of LG Innotek.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Developer logs showed that at least nine Mac models with four different M2 chips were being tested.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In April 2022, Apple opened an online store that allowed anyone in the US to view repair manuals and order replacement parts for specific recent iPhones, although the difference in cost between this method and official repair is anticipated to be minimal.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In May 2022, a trademark was filed for RealityOS, an operating system reportedly intended for virtual and augmented reality headsets, first mentioned in 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] According to Bloomberg, the headset may come out in 2023.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Further insider reports state that the device uses iris scanning for payment confirmation and signing into accounts.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2023, Apple formally announced its first mixed reality headset, the Apple Vision Pro, which ran its new visionOS operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The headset was released in February of the following year.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On June 18, 2022, the Apple Store in Towson, Maryland, became the first to unionize in the US, with the employees voting to join the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On July 7, 2022, Apple added Lockdown Mode to macOS 13 and iOS 16, as a response to the earlier Pegasus revelations; the mode increases security protections for high-risk users against targeted zero-day malware.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple launched a buy now, pay later service called 'Apple Pay Later' for its Apple Wallet users in March 2023.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The program allows its users to apply for loans between $50 and $1,000 to make online or in-app purchases and then repaying them through four installments spread over six weeks without any interest or fees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In November 2023, Apple agreed to a $25-million settlement in a US Department of Justice case that alleged Apple was discriminating against US citizens in hiring.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple created jobs that were not listed online and that required a paper submission application, while advertising these jobs to foreign workers as part of recruitment for PERM.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In January 2024, Apple announced compliance with the European Union's competition law, with major changes to the App Store and other services, effective on March 7.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This enables iOS users in the 27-nation bloc to use alternative app stores, and alternative payment methods within apps.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This adds a menu in Safari for downloading alternative browsers, such as Chrome or Firefox.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In June 2024, Apple introduced Apple Intelligence to incorporate on-device artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In October 2024, Apple introduced its Apple Intelligence suite, bringing generative AI features such as writing assistance, enhanced Siri capabilities, and improved photo tools to select iPhone, iPad, and Mac devices.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On November 1, 2024, Apple announced its acquisition of Pixelmator, a company known for its image editing applications for iPhone and Mac.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple had previously showcased Pixelmator's apps during its product launches, including naming Pixelmator Pro its Mac App of the Year in 2018 for its innovative use of machine learning and AI.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In the announcement, Pixelmator stated that there would be no significant changes to its existing apps following the acquisition.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On December 31, 2024, a preliminary settlement was filed in the Oakland California federal court that accused Apple of unlawfully recording private conversations, through unintentional Siri activations, and of sharing them with third parties, including advertisers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple agreed to a $95-million cash settlement to resolve this lawsuit in which its Siri assistant violated user privacy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] While denying any wrongdoing, Apple settled the case, allowing affected users to potentially claim up to $20 per device.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Attorneys sought $28.5 million in fees from the settlement fund.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2025, Apple undertook its largest investment initiative to date, announcing a commitment to spend over $500 billion in the United States over the following four years.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] This extensive strategy includes the opening of a new manufacturing facility in Houston to produce servers supporting Apple Intelligence, expansion of research and development in fields like silicon engineering and AI, and the establishment of a new advanced manufacturing academy in Detroit.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company also pledged to double its US Advanced Manufacturing Fund and increase collaboration with American suppliers, aiming to create tens of thousands of jobs related to R&D, AI, and manufacturing technologies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The software landscape at Apple underwent a transformation in 2025.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] At its Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC), Apple introduced the new "Liquid Glass" design language, rolled out unified system design updates across iOS 26, iPadOS 26, macOS Tahoe, and other platforms, and significantly expanded the capabilities of Apple Intelligence.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] According to Apple, these updates were intended to address previous criticisms of fragmented interfaces and to use on‑device and cloud‑based AI to improve privacy and user experience.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Despite continued growth in its services sector, including a new all-time high for services revenue in the March quarter and the launch of updated models such as the iPhone 16e and M4 MacBook Air, Apple faced significant challenges.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The company contended with a 19% decline in stock value year-to-date, ongoing antitrust investigations by the US Department of Justice, and legal disputes involving the App Store.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Competition in the AI space escalated, with rivals gaining ground.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] High-profile departures and political tensions, including calls for Apple to manufacture iPhones domestically or face tariffs, added to the pressure, have been cited by analysts as contributing to a difficult year for CEO Tim Cook.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In December 2025, Cook met with US House members to push back against the App Store Accountability Act which could require that Apple authenticates users' ages and possibly collect sensitive data on children.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On January 12, 2026, Apple announced a partnership with Google Gemini for AI-powered Siri.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In January 2026, Apple acquired Q.ai, an Israeli artificial intelligence startup specializing in imaging and machine learning technologies for audio processing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The financial terms were not disclosed, though media reports estimated the acquisition at nearly US$2 billion; this is Apple's second-largest purchase to date.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Following the deal, Q.ai's founders and approximately 100 employees joined Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In February 2026, US lawmakers requested that the United Kingdom government provide a briefing on its now-rescinded order for Apple to build a backdoor into its encrypted devices, expressing concerns about privacy and security implications of such access.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] On April 20, 2026, Apple announced that Tim Cook will step down as CEO on September 1, 2026, to be succeeded by John Ternus, the Senior Vice President of Hardware Engineering.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Cook is slated to become Executive Chairman of the Board, while Arthur Levinson, the long-standing non-executive chairman, will transition to the role of Lead Independent Director.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Since the company's founding and into the early 2000s, Apple primarily sold computers, which are marketed as Macintosh since the mid-1980s.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Since then, the company has expanded its product categories to include various portable devices, starting with the now discontinued iPod (2001), and later the iPhone (2007) and iPad (2010).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also sells several other products that it categorizes as "Wearables, Home and Accessories", such as the Apple Watch, Apple TV, AirPods, HomePod, and Apple Vision Pro.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of 2023, there were over 2 billion Apple devices in active use worldwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Cory Doctorow, a Canadian intellectual property researcher and activist, characterized Apple's strategy of promoting interoperability with its own products while simultaneously reducing functionality for competitors as an anti-competitive practice.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Mac, which is short for Macintosh, its official name until 1999, is Apple's line of personal computers that use the company's proprietary macOS operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Personal computers were Apple's original business line, but as of the end of 2024 they account for only about eight percent of the company's revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Macs use Apple silicon chips, run the macOS operating system, and include Apple software like the Safari web browser, iMovie for home movie editing, GarageBand for music creation, and the iWork productivity suite.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also sells pro apps: Final Cut Pro for video production, Logic Pro for musicians and producers, and Xcode for software developers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also sells a variety of accessories for Macs, including the Studio Display and Studio Display XDR, Magic Mouse, Magic Trackpad, and Magic Keyboard.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of 2026, the series of Mac include either the M5 Apple silicon chip, available in the MacBook Pro and MacBook Air, and the A18 Pro–powered MacBook Neo, the company's first ostensibly 'entry level' MacBook product.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPhone is Apple's line of smartphones, which run the company's iOS operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The first iPhone was unveiled by Steve Jobs on January 9, 2007.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Since then, new iPhone models have been released every year.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] When it was introduced, its multi-touch screen was described as "revolutionary" and a "game-changer" for the mobile phone industry.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The device has been credited with creating the app economy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] iOS is one of the two major smartphone platforms in the world, alongside Android.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPhone has generated large profits for the company, and is credited with helping to make Apple one of the world's most valuable publicly traded companies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of the end of 2024, the iPhone accounts for nearly half of the company's revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPad is Apple's line of tablets, which run the company's iPadOS operating system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The first-generation iPad was announced on January 27, 2010.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPad is mainly marketed for consuming multimedia, creating art, working on documents, videoconferencing, and playing games.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPad lineup consists of several base iPad models, and the smaller iPad Mini, upgraded iPad Air, and high-end iPad Pro.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple has consistently improved the iPad's performance, with the iPad Pro adopting the same M-series chips as the Mac, though the iPad continues to receive criticism for its limited OS.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of September 2020, Apple has sold more than 500 million iPads, though sales peaked in 2013.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] The iPad remains the most popular tablet computer by sales as of the second quarter of 2020, and accounted for seven percent of the company's revenue as of the end of 2024.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple sells several iPad accessories, including the Apple Pencil, Smart Keyboard, Smart Keyboard Folio, Magic Keyboard, and several adapters.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple makes several other products that it categorizes as "Wearables, Home and Accessories".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] These products include the AirPods line of wireless headphones, Apple TV digital media players, Apple Watch smartwatches, Beats headphones, HomePod smart speakers, and the Vision Pro mixed reality headset.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of the end of 2024, this broad line of products comprises about ten percent of the company's revenues.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] Apple also provides Apple One, which is a bundle of these services.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] In 2019, Apple announced it would be making a concerted effort to expand its service revenues.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p01] As of the end of 2024, services comprise about 26% of the company's revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to Steve Jobs, the company's name was inspired by his visit to an apple farm while on a fruitarian diet.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's first logo, designed by Ron Wayne, depicts Sir Isaac Newton sitting under an apple tree.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] It was almost immediately replaced by Rob Janoff's "rainbow Apple", the now-familiar rainbow-colored silhouette of an apple with a bite taken out of it.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This logo has been erroneously referred to as a tribute to Alan Turing, with the bite mark a reference to his method of suicide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On August 27, 1999, Apple officially dropped the rainbow scheme and began to use single-color logos nearly identical in shape to the previous rainbow incarnation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] An Aqua-themed version of the logo was used from 1997 until 2003, and a glass-themed version was used from 2007 until 2013.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple evangelists were actively engaged by the company at one time, but this was after the phenomenon had already been firmly established.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple evangelist Guy Kawasaki has called the brand fanaticism "something that was stumbled upon", while Jonathan Ive claimed in 2014 that "people have an incredibly personal relationship" with Apple's products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's first slogan, "Byte into an Apple", was coined in the late 1970s.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] From 1997 to 2002, the slogan "Think different" was used in advertising campaigns, and is still closely associated with Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple also has slogans for specific product lines—for example, "iThink, therefore iMac" was used in 1998 to promote the iMac, and "Say hello to iPhone" has been used in iPhone advertisements.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] "Hello" was also used to introduce the original Macintosh, Newton, iMac ("hello (again)"), and iPod.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] From the introduction of the Macintosh in 1984, with the 1984 Super Bowl advertisement to the more modern Get a Mac adverts, Apple has been recognized for its efforts toward effective advertising and marketing for its products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] However, claims made by later campaigns were criticized, particularly the 2005 Power Mac ads.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's product advertisements gained significant attention as a result of their graphics and song choice.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Musicians who benefited from an improved profile as a result of their songs being included on Apple advertisements include Canadian singer Feist with the song "1234" and Yael Naïm with the song "New Soul".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The first Apple Stores were originally opened as two locations in May 2001 by then-CEO Steve Jobs, after years of attempting but failing store-within-a-store concepts.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Seeing a need for improved retail presentation of the company's products, he began an effort in 1997 to revamp the retail program to get an improved relationship to consumers, and hired Ron Johnson in 2000.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Jobs relaunched Apple's online store in 1997, and opened the first two physical stores in 2001.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The media initially speculated that Apple would fail, but they exceeded the sales numbers of competing nearby stores, and within three years reached US$1 billion in annual sales, becoming the fastest retailer in history to do so.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Over the years, Apple has expanded the number of retail locations and its geographical coverage, with 499 stores across 22 countries worldwide as of December 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Strong product sales have placed Apple among the top-tier retail stores, with sales over $16 billion globally in 2011.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple Stores underwent a period of significant redesign, beginning in May 2016.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This redesign included physical changes to the Apple Stores, such as open spaces and re-branded rooms, and changes in function to facilitate interaction between consumers and professionals.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Many Apple Stores are located inside shopping malls, but Apple has built several stand-alone "flagship" stores in high-profile locations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] It has been granted design patents and received architectural awards for its stores' designs and construction, specifically for its use of glass staircases and cubes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The success of Apple Stores have had significant influence over other consumer electronics retailers, which have lost traffic, control and profits due to a perceived higher quality of service and products at Apple Stores.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Due to the popularity of the brand, Apple receives a large number of job applications, many of which come from young workers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Although Apple Store employees receive above-average pay, are offered money toward education and health care, and receive product discounts, there are limited or no paths of career advancement.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On March 16, 2020, France fined Apple €1.1 billion for colluding with two wholesalers to stifle competition and keep prices high by impeding independent resellers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The arrangement created aligned prices for Apple products such as iPads and personal computers for about half the French retail market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to the French regulators, the abuses occurred between 2005 and 2017 but were first discovered after a complaint by an independent reseller, eBizcuss, in 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On August 13, 2020, Epic Games, the maker of the popular game *Fortnite*, sued Apple and Google after *Fortnite* was removed from Apple's and Google's app stores.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The lawsuits came after Apple and Google blocked the game after it introduced a direct payment system that bypassed the fees that Apple and Google had imposed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In September 2020, Epic Games founded the Coalition for App Fairness together with thirteen other companies, which aims for better conditions for the inclusion of apps in the app stores.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Later, in December 2020, Facebook agreed to assist Epic in its legal game against Apple, planning to support the company by providing materials and documents to Epic.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Facebook had, however, stated that the company would not participate directly with the lawsuit, although did commit to helping with the discovery of evidence relating to the trial of 2021.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In the months prior to their agreement, Facebook had been dealing with feuds against Apple relating to the prices of paid apps and privacy rule changes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has publicly taken a pro-privacy stance, actively making privacy-conscious features and settings part of its conferences, promotional campaigns, and public image.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] With its iOS 8 mobile operating system in 2014, the company started encrypting all contents of iOS devices through users' passcodes, making it impossible at the time for the company to provide customer data to law enforcement requests seeking such information.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] With the popularity rise of cloud storage solutions, Apple began a technique in 2016 to do deep learning scans for facial data in photos on the user's local device and encrypting the content before uploading it to Apple's iCloud storage system.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] It also introduced "differential privacy", a way to collect crowdsourced data from many users, while keeping individual users anonymous, in a system that *Wired* described as "trying to learn as much as possible about a group while learning as little as possible about any individual in it".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Users are explicitly asked if they want to participate, and can actively opt-in or opt-out.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] With Apple's release of an update to iOS 14, Apple required all developers of iPhone, iPad, and iPod Touch applications to directly ask iPhone users permission to track them.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The feature, called "App Tracking Transparency", received heavy criticism from Facebook, whose primary business model revolves around the tracking of users' data and sharing such data with advertisers so users can see more relevant ads, a technique commonly known as targeted advertising.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] After Facebook's measures, including purchasing full-page newspaper advertisements protesting App Tracking Transparency, Apple released the update in early 2021.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] A study by Verizon subsidiary Flurry Analytics reported only 4% of iOS users in the United States and 12% worldwide have opted into tracking.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Prior to the release of iOS 15, Apple announced new efforts at combating child sexual abuse material on iOS and Mac platforms.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Parents of minor iMessage users can now be alerted if their child sends or receives nude photographs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Additionally, on-device hashing would take place on media destined for upload to iCloud, and hashes would be compared to a list of known abusive images provided by law enforcement; if enough matches were found, Apple would be alerted and authorities informed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The new features received praise from law enforcement and victims rights advocates.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] However, privacy advocates, including the Electronic Frontier Foundation, condemned the new features as invasive and highly prone to abuse by authoritarian governments.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Ireland's Data Protection Commission launched a privacy investigation to examine whether Apple complied with the EU's GDPR law following an investigation into how the company processes personal data with targeted ads on its platform.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In December 2019, security researcher Brian Krebs discovered that the iPhone 11 Pro would still show the arrow indicator–signifying location services are being used–at the top of the screen while the main location services toggle is enabled, despite all individual location services being disabled.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Krebs was unable to replicate this behavior on older models and when asking Apple for comment, he was told by Apple that "It is expected behavior that the Location Services icon appears in the status bar when Location Services is enabled.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple promised to add a new toggle for this feature and in later iOS revisions Apple provided users with the option to tap on the location services indicator in Control Center to see which specific service is using the device's location.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to published reports by Bloomberg News on March 30, 2022, Apple turned over data such as phone numbers, physical addresses, and IP addresses to hackers posing as law enforcement officials using forged documents.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The law enforcement requests sometimes included forged signatures of real or fictional officials.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple is one of several highly successful companies founded in the 1970s that bucked the traditional notions of corporate culture.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Jobs often walked around the office barefoot even after Apple became a *Fortune* 500 company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] By the time of the "1984" television advertisement, Apple's informal culture had become a key trait that differentiated it from its competitors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to a 2011 report in *Fortune*, this has resulted in a corporate culture more akin to a startup rather than a multinational corporation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In a 2017 interview, Wozniak credited watching *Star Trek* and attending *Star Trek* conventions in his youth as inspiration for co-founding Apple.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As the company has grown and been led by a series of differently opinionated chief executives, some media have suggested that it has lost some of its original character.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Nonetheless, it has maintained a reputation for fostering individuality and excellence that reliably attracts talented workers, particularly after Jobs returned.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Numerous Apple employees have stated that projects without Jobs' involvement often took longer than others.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The Apple Fellows program awards employees for extraordinary technical or leadership contributions to personal computing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Recipients include Bill Atkinson, Steve Capps, Rod Holt, Alan Kay, Guy Kawasaki, Al Alcorn, Don Norman, Rich Page, Steve Wozniak, and Phil Schiller.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Jobs intended that employees were to be specialists who are not exposed to functions outside their area of expertise.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] For instance, Ron Johnson—Senior Vice President of Retail Operations until November 1, 2011—was responsible for site selection, in-store service, and store layout, yet had no control of the inventory in his stores.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This was done by Tim Cook, who had a background in supply-chain management.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple is known for strictly enforcing accountability.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Each project has a "directly responsible individual" or "DRI" in Apple jargon.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Unlike other major US companies, Apple provides a relatively simple compensation policy for executives that does not include perks enjoyed by other CEOs like country club fees or private use of company aircraft.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company typically grants stock options to executives every other year.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This increased to 116,000 full-time employees the next year, a notable hiring decrease, largely due to its first revenue decline.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple does not specify how many of its employees work in retail, though its 2014 SEC filing put the number at approximately half of its employee base.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In September 2017, Apple announced that it had over 123,000 full-time employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has a strong culture of corporate secrecy, and has an anti-leak Global Security team that recruits from the National Security Agency, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, and the United States Secret Service.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In December 2017, Glassdoor said Apple was the 48th best place to work, having originally entered at rank 19 in 2009, peaking at rank 10 in 2012, and falling down the ranks in subsequent years.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2023, Bloomberg's Mark Gurman revealed the existence of Apple's Exploratory Design Group (XDG), which was working to add glucose monitoring to the Apple Watch.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Gurman compared XDG to Alphabet's X "moonshot factory".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has faced criticism regarding its market practices, labor conditions, and privacy policies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company has been criticized for alleged anti-competitive behavior and its alleged participation in the PRISM surveillance program.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Significant concerns have been raised about labor issues in its supply chain, restrictions on the right to repair, and the company's tax strategies and environmental impact.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Furthermore, Apple has faced scrutiny for its business operations in nations with restrictive human rights records, such as China.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On May 5, 2026, Apple settled for $250 million a shareholder lawsuit after the lawsuit was filed by Peter Landsheft in US federal court in California in 2024 over delays in AI upgrades to Siri.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's world corporate headquarters are located in Cupertino, in the middle of California's Silicon Valley, at Apple Park, a massive circular groundscraper building with a circumference of one mile (1.6 km).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The building opened in April 2017 and houses more than 12,000 employees.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple co-founder Steve Jobs wanted Apple Park to look less like a business park and more like a nature refuge, and personally appeared before the Cupertino City Council in June 2011 to make the proposal, in his final public appearance before his death.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple also operates from the Apple Campus (also known by its address, 1 Infinite Loop), a grouping of six buildings in Cupertino that total 850,000 square feet (79,000 m2) located about 1 mile (1.6 km) to the west of Apple Park.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The Apple Campus was the company's headquarters from its opening in 1993, until the opening of Apple Park in 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The buildings, located at 1–6 Infinite Loop, are arranged in a circular pattern around a central green space, in a design that has been compared to that of a university.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In addition to Apple Park and the Apple Campus, Apple occupies an additional thirty office buildings scattered throughout the city of Cupertino, including three buildings as prior headquarters: Stephens Creek Three from 1977 to 1978, Bandley One from 1978 to 1982, and Mariani One from 1982 to 1993.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In total, Apple occupies almost 40% of the available office space in the city.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's headquarters for Europe, the Middle East and Africa (EMEA) are located in Cork in the south of Ireland, called the Hollyhill campus.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The facility, which opened in 1980, houses 5,500 people and was Apple's first location outside of the United States.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's international sales and distribution arms operate out of the campus in Cork.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company also has several other locations in Boulder, Colorado; Culver City, California; Herzliya (Israel), London, New York, Pittsburgh, San Diego, and Seattle that each employ hundreds of people.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has been a participant in various legal proceedings and claims since it began operation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In particular, Apple is known for and promotes itself as actively and aggressively enforcing its intellectual property interests.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Some litigation examples include *Apple v.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has also had to defend itself against charges on numerous occasions of violating intellectual property rights.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Most have been dismissed in the courts as shell companies known as patent trolls, with no evidence of actual use of patents in question.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On December 21, 2016, Nokia announced that in the US and Germany, it has filed a suit against Apple, claiming that the latter's products infringe on Nokia's patents.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Epic Games filed a lawsuit against Apple in August 2020 in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California, related to Apple's practices in the App Store for iOS.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In January 2022, Ericsson sued Apple over payment of royalty of 5G technology.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On June 24, 2024, the European Commission accused Apple of violating the Digital Markets Act by preventing "app developers from freely steering consumers to alternative channels for offers and content".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In April 2025, Apple was found guilty and fined €500 million ($570 million) for violating the Digital Markets Act.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2025, Apple was one of the donors who funded the White House's East Wing demolition, and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of 2024, Apple was the world's fourth-largest personal computer vendor, the largest vendor of tablet computers, and the largest vendor of mobile phones.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In its fiscal year ending in September 2011, Apple reported a total of $108 billion in annual revenues—a significant increase from its 2010 revenues of $65 billion—and nearly $82 billion in cash reserves.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On March 19, 2012, Apple announced plans for a $2.65-per-share dividend beginning in the fourth quarter of 2012, per approval by its board of directors.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company's worldwide annual revenue in 2013 totaled $170 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In May 2013, Apple entered the top ten of the *Fortune* 500 list of companies for the first time, rising 11 places above its 2012 ranking to take the sixth position.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of 2016, Apple has around US$234 billion of cash and marketable securities, of which 90% is located outside the United States for tax purposes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple amassed 65% of all profits made by the eight largest worldwide smartphone manufacturers in quarter one of 2014, according to a report by Canaccord Genuity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In the first quarter of 2015, the company garnered 92% of all earnings.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On April 30, 2017, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Apple had cash reserves of $250 billion, officially confirmed by Apple as specifically $256.8 billion a few days later.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of August 3, 2018, Apple was the largest publicly traded corporation in the world by market capitalization.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On August 2, 2018, Apple became the first publicly traded US company to reach a $1 trillion market value, and, as of October 2025, is valued at just over $4 trillion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] 3 on the 2023 *Fortune* 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by revenue.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In July 2022, Apple reported an 11% decline in Q3 profits compared to 2021.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Its revenue in the same period rose 2% year-on-year to $83 billion, though this figure was also lower than in 2021, where the increase was at 36%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The general downturn is reportedly caused by the slowing global economy and supply chain disruptions in China.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] That year, Apple was one of the largest corporate spenders on research and development worldwide, with R&D expenditure amounting to over $27 billion.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In May 2023, Apple reported a decline in its sales for the first quarter of 2023.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Compared to that of 2022, revenue for 2023 fell by 3%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This is Apple's second consecutive quarter of sales decline.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This fall is attributed to the slowing economy and consumers putting off purchases of iPads and computers due to increased pricing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] However, iPhone sales held up with a year-on-year increase of 1.5%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to Apple, demands for such devices were strong, particularly in Latin America and South Asia.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has created subsidiaries in low-tax places such as Ireland, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, and the British Virgin Islands to cut the taxes it pays around the world.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to *The New York Times*, in the 1980s Apple was among the first tech companies to designate overseas salespeople in high-tax countries in a manner that allowed the company to sell on behalf of low-tax subsidiaries on other continents, sidestepping income taxes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In the late 1980s, Apple was a pioneer of an accounting technique known as the "Double Irish with a Dutch sandwich", which reduces taxes by routing profits through Irish subsidiaries and the Netherlands and then to the Caribbean.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] He followed this research by calling on the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne to force these multinationals, which also included Google and the Coca-Cola Company, to state the effective rate of tax it pays on its UK revenues.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Elphicke also said that government contracts should be withheld from multinationals who do not pay their fair share of UK tax.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to a US Senate report on the company's offshore tax structure concluded in May 2013, Apple has held billions of dollars in profits in Irish subsidiaries to pay little or no taxes to any government by using an unusual global tax structure.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The main subsidiary, a holding company that includes Apple's retail stores throughout Europe, has not paid any corporate income tax in the last five years.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] "Apple has exploited a difference between Irish and U.S. tax residency rules", the report said.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On May 21, 2013, Apple CEO Tim Cook defended his company's tax tactics at a Senate hearing.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple says that it is the single largest taxpayer in the US, with an effective tax rate of approximately of 26% as of Q2 FY2016.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In an interview with the German newspaper *FAZ* in October 2017, Tim Cook stated that Apple was the biggest taxpayer worldwide.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2016, after a two-year investigation, the European Commission claimed that Apple's use of a hybrid Double Irish tax arrangement constituted "illegal state aid" from Ireland, and ordered Apple to pay €13 billion ($14.5 billion) in unpaid taxes, the largest corporate tax fine in history.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] This was later annulled, after the European General Court ruled that the commission had provided insufficient evidence.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2018, Apple repatriated $285 billion to the United States, resulting in a $38-billion tax payment spread over the following eight years.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple is a partner of Product Red, a fundraising campaign for AIDS charity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In November 2014, Apple arranged for all App Store revenue in a two-week period to go to the fundraiser, generating more than US$20 million, and in March 2017, it released an iPhone 7 with a red color finish.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of 2021, Apple has donated over $250 million to Product Red.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple contributes financially to fundraisers in times of natural disasters.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In November 2012, it donated $2.5 million to the American Red Cross to aid relief efforts after Hurricane Sandy, and in 2017 it donated $5 million to relief efforts for both Hurricane Irma and Hurricane Harvey, and for the 2017 Central Mexico earthquake.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company has used its iTunes platform to encourage donations in the wake of environmental disasters and humanitarian crises, such as the 2010 Haiti earthquake, the 2011 Japan earthquake, Typhoon Haiyan in the Philippines in November 2013, and the 2015 European migrant crisis.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On April 14, 2016, Apple and the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) announced that they have engaged in a partnership to, "help protect life on our planet".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple released a special page in its App Store, Apps for Earth.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In the arrangement, Apple has committed that through April 24, WWF will receive 100% of the proceeds from the applications participating in the App Store via both the purchases of any paid apps and the In-App Purchases.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple and WWF's Apps for Earth campaign raised more than $8 million in total proceeds to support WWF's conservation work.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] WWF announced the results at WWDC 2016 in San Francisco.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Apple's CEO Cook announced that the company would be donating "millions" of masks to health workers in the United States and Europe.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On January 13, 2021, Apple announced a $100-million Racial Equity and Justice Initiative to help combat institutional racism worldwide after the 2020 murder of George Floyd.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In June 2023, Apple announced that it was doubling this and then distributed more than $200 million to support organizations focused on education, economic growth, and criminal justice.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Half is philanthropic grants and half is centered on equity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple Energy, LLC is a wholly owned subsidiary of Apple that sells solar energy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of June 6, 2016, Apple's solar farms in California and Nevada have been declared to provide 217.9 megawatts of solar generation capacity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has received regulatory approval to construct a landfill gas energy plant in North Carolina to use the methane emissions to generate electricity.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple's North Carolina data center is already powered entirely by renewable sources.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2010, Climate Counts, a nonprofit organization dedicated to directing consumers toward the greenest companies, gave Apple a score of 52 points out of a possible 100, which puts Apple in its top category "Striding".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Following a Greenpeace protest, Apple released a statement on April 17, 2012, committing to ending its use of coal and shifting to 100% renewable clean energy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] By 2013, Apple was using 100% renewable energy to power its data centers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Overall, 75% of the company's power came from clean renewable sources.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of 2016, Apple states that 100% of its US operations run on renewable energy, 100% of Apple's data centers run on renewable energy and 93% of Apple's global operations run on renewable energy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] However, the facilities are connected to the local grid which usually contains a mix of fossil and renewable sources, so Apple uses carbon offsets for its electricity use.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The Electronic Product Environmental Assessment Tool (EPEAT) allows consumers to see the effect a product has on the environment.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Each product receives a Gold, Silver, or Bronze rank depending on its efficiency and sustainability.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Every Apple tablet, notebook, desktop computer, and display that EPEAT ranks achieves a Gold rating, the highest possible.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Although Apple's data centers recycle water 35 times, the increased activity in retail, corporate and data centers also increase the amount of water use to 573 million US gal (2.2 million m3) in 2015.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] During an event on March 21, 2016, Apple provided a status update on its environmental initiative to be 100% renewable in all of its worldwide operations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Jackson, Apple's vice president of Environment, Policy and Social Initiatives who reports directly to CEO, Tim Cook, announced that as of March 2016, 93% of Apple's worldwide operations are powered with renewable energy.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Also featured was the company's efforts to use sustainable paper in its product packaging; 99% of all paper used by Apple in the product packaging comes from post-consumer recycled paper or sustainably managed forests, as the company continues its move to all paper packaging for all of its products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple announced on August 16, 2016, that Lens Technology, one of its major suppliers in China, has committed to power all its glass production for Apple with 100 percent renewable energy by 2018.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The commitment was a large step in Apple's efforts to help manufacturers lower their carbon footprint in China.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple also announced that all 14 of its final assembly sites in China are now compliant with UL's Zero Waste to Landfill validation.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The standard, which started in January 2015, certifies that all manufacturing waste is reused, recycled, composted, or converted into energy (when necessary).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Since the program began, nearly 140,000 metric tons of waste have been diverted from landfills.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] On July 21, 2020, Apple announced its plan to become carbon neutral across its entire business, manufacturing supply chain, and product life cycle by 2030.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In the next 10 years, Apple will try to lower emissions with a series of innovative actions, including: low carbon product design, expanding energy efficiency, renewable energy, process and material innovations, and carbon removal.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In June 2024, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) published a report about an electronic computer manufacturing facility leased by Apple in 2015 in Santa Clara, California, code named Aria.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The EPA report stated that Apple was potentially in violation of federal regulations under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] According to a report from *Bloomberg* in 2018, the facility is used to develop microLED screens under the code name T159.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The inspection found that Apple was potentially mistreating waste as only subject to California regulations and that it had potentially miscalculated the effectiveness of Apple's activated carbon filters, which filter volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from the air.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The EPA inspected the facility in August 2023 due to a tip from a former Apple employee who posted the report on X.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Following further campaigns by Greenpeace, in 2008, Apple became the first electronics manufacturer to eliminate all polyvinyl chloride (PVC) and brominated flame retardants (BFRs) in its complete product line.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In June 2007, Apple began replacing the cold cathode fluorescent lamp (CCFL) backlit LCDs in its computers with mercury-free LED-backlit LCD and arsenic-free glass, starting with the upgraded MacBook Pro.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple offers comprehensive and transparent information about the CO2e, emissions, materials, and electrical usage concerning every product it currently produces or has sold in the past (and which it has enough data needed to produce the report), in its portfolio on its homepage.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Allowing consumers to make informed purchasing decisions on the products it offers for sale.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In June 2009, Apple's iPhone 3GS was free of PVC, arsenic, and BFRs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Since 2009, all Apple products have mercury-free LED-backlit LCDs, arsenic-free glass, and non-PVC cables.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] All Apple products have EPEAT Gold status and beat the latest Energy Star guidelines in each product's respective regulatory category.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In November 2011, Apple was featured in Greenpeace's Guide to Greener Electronics, which ranks electronics manufacturers on sustainability, climate and energy policy, and how "green" its products are.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company ranked fourth of fifteen electronics companies (moving up five places from the previous year) with a score of 4.6/10.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Greenpeace praised Apple's sustainability, noting that the company exceeded its 70% global recycling goal in 2010.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple continues to score well on product ratings, with all of its products now being free of PVC plastic and BFRs.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] However, the guide criticized Apple on the Energy criteria for not seeking external verification of its greenhouse gas emissions data, and for not setting any targets to reduce emissions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In January 2012, Apple requested that its cable maker, Volex, begin producing halogen-free USB and power cables.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In February 2016, Apple issued a US$1.5-billion green bond (climate bond), the first ever of its kind by a US tech company.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The green bond proceeds are dedicated to the financing of environmental projects.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] As of 2018, Apple used hardware components from 43 different countries.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple products were made in the United States in Apple-owned factories until the late 1990s; however, as a result of outsourcing initiatives in the 2000s, almost all of its manufacturing is now handled abroad.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] South Korean firms, including Samsung and LG, worked closely with Apple as parts partners for the iMac, iPod, and iPhone before it increased its reliance on Taiwan and China.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Taiwanese Apple suppliers such as Foxconn, Wistron, Pegatron, Quanta, and Compal Electronics established a sizable manufacturing presence in China.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] By the 2020s, orders were shifting to Chinese firms such as to Luxshare, BYD Electronic, Goertek, and Wingtech.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] By 2021, Apple had more suppliers from China than Taiwan.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The company's manufacturing, procurement, and logistics enable it to execute massive product launches without having to maintain large, profit-sapping inventories.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2011, Apple's profit margins were 40 percent, compared with between 10 and 20 percent for most other hardware companies.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple directly employs 147,000 workers including 25,000 corporate employees in Apple Park and across Silicon Valley.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The vast majority of its employees work at the over 500 retail Apple Stores globally.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple relies on a larger, outsourced workforce for manufacturing, particularly in China where Apple directly employs 10,000 workers across its retail and corporate divisions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In addition, one further million workers are contracted by Apple's suppliers to assemble Apple products, including Foxconn and Pegatron.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Zhengzhou Technology Park alone employs 350,000 Chinese workers in Zhengzhou to exclusively work on the iPhone.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple workers around the globe have been involved in organizing since the 1990s.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple unions are made up of retail, corporate, and outsourced workers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple employees have joined trade unions or formed works councils in Australia, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] In 2021, Apple Together, a solidarity union, sought to bring together the company's global worker organizations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] The majority of industrial labor disputes (including union recognition) involving Apple occur indirectly through its suppliers and contractors, notably Foxconn plants in China and, to a lesser extent, in Brazil and India.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/apple-inc-p02] Apple has been criticized for labor sourcing and conditions at the facilities of its contract manufacturers as well as mines.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 2010, Hitachi Data Systems sold through direct and indirect channels in more than 170 countries and regions, with customers that included over half of the Fortune 100 companies at the time.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] It was a subsidiary of Hitachi and part of the Hitachi Information Systems & Telecommunications Division until 2017.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 2017, it merged with Pentaho and Hitachi Insight Group to form Hitachi Vantara.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Itel was founded in 1967 by Peter Redfield and Gary Friedman as an equipment leasing company and initially focused on leasing IBM mainframes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Through creative financial arrangements and investments, Itel began to lease IBM mainframes to customers at lower costs, which led to Itel ranking second to IBM in revenues.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 1977, a joint venture between National Semiconductor and Hitachi formed, and was contracted by Itel to manufacture IBM-compatible mainframes branded as Advanced Systems.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] After initial success shipping 200 such systems and net profits of $73 million, Itel increased investments and personnel to market its Advanced Systems brand.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] When Itel requested lower prices to compete with IBM, the CEO of National Semiconductor Charlie Sporck, persuaded Itel to commit to long-term contracts with National Semiconductor and Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] When news leaked that IBM was releasing a superior line of computers, customers held back purchases of Itel goods, causing Itel's inventory to build up drastically.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi agreed to Itel's request to cut back on shipment, but National Semiconductor insisted that National had blackmailed Itel.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 1979, Redfield was forced to resign as CEO.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] National Semiconductor took over Itel Advanced Systems' sales and marketing divisions.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] National Semiconductor renamed the National Advanced Systems (NAS) division, assembling and selling IBM-compatibles where the central processing unit (CPU) was imported from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] National and Hitachi relied upon IBM's gradual and restrained roll-out of newer models to support IBM's technology and market share, which supported NAS's occasional successes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] National Semiconductor and its subsidiary NAS were sued in 1983 by IBM for $2.5 billion on charges of using computer technology secrets stolen from IBM, as the result of an investigation by the United States Government into National's collaboration with Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi settled with IBM and licensed the mainframe operating system software from IBM.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 1983, NAS ceased manufacturing its line of mainframes (which had Hitachi processors) and became a reseller of Hitachi's mainframe and data storage products.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi Data Systems (HDS) was founded in 1989 when Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) acquired National Advanced Systems (NAS) from National Semiconductor and renamed it Hitachi Data Systems.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Before that, the origins of the company had a history that stretched back to Itel, an early player in the mainframe market.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Intel's Computer Products Group sold National Semiconductors' IBM plug compatible mainframes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 1979 National Semiconductor took over Itel and formed National Advanced Systems (NAS).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] NAS shifted from manufacturing mainframes and began marketing systems from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 1999, Hitachi bought out EDS's share, and HDS became a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] For many years, HDS sold Hitachi IBM plug-compatible mainframes and storage systems, but in 2000, it exited the mainframe business and shifted its focus to enterprise storage.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] On February 28, 1989, National Semiconductor and Hitachi announced their agreement that Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) would jointly acquire NAS for $398 million in cash, of which Hitachi would own 80%.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Memorex Telex and National had earlier, on January 10, 1989, announced plans on a joint venture "under which each company would own half of the unit and National would get $250 million plus four million shares of Memorex Telex".
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] By that time, Memorex Telex was able to arrange financing for the deal, but National had already accepted the Hitachi–EDS deal.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] The acquisition was envisaged to provide Hitachi with a better presence in the United States to compete with IBM.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] The entity was renamed Hitachi Data Systems (HDS).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] On January 29, 1999, Hitachi announced it would take over EDS' stake in HDS, appointing Jun Naruse as CEO of its new subsidiary.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Naruse was an engineer with the RAID Systems Division who was involved in developing storage systems.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Having total control of the company, Hitachi infused Hitachi Data Systems with its corporate culture, ethics, and practices.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] On April 6, 2000, Hitachi Data Systems announced a re-organization to focus on storage systems rather than mainframes.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Shortly thereafter (June 26, 2000), the first HDS storage product was unveiled, the Freedom Storage Lightning 9900, featuring the crossbar switched architecture to interconnect memory, disks, servers, and other external devices instead of the traditional bus architecture.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In addition to HDS sales, HP OEM’d and Sun resold the 9900 and succeeding generations, which had additional capabilities such as virtualization of external Hitachi and third-party storage systems to form storage pools.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In January 2001, HDS announced the Thunder 9200, a mid-range modular storage system aimed at the small and medium business market, sold mainly through resellers.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi Data Systems high-end and mid-range modular storage systems were complemented by software for storage management, content management, business continuity, replication, data protection, and IT operations.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 2002, Hitachi acquired Comstock Systems Corp, and analysts estimated that the acquisition would lead to a 35% percent market share.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] HDS moved to use the term cloud computing, culminating with an announcement on October 25, 2011.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In August 2014, in partnership with Avnet, HDS announced cloud partners.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] The corporate headquarters are in Santa Clara, California, with business offices in the United States, Australia and New Zealand, Canada, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] The culture of Hitachi Vantara is influenced by the values of Hitachi: wa (harmony, trust, and respect), Makoto (integrity, honesty), and kaitakusha-seishin (pioneering spirit and challenges).
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi Data Systems appeared in *Fortune* magazine's "100 Best Companies to Work For" list in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and was ranked No.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] 8 in the *Fortune* list of top-paying companies in 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Chief Executive Magazine gave HDS a ranking of No.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] 16 in its “40 Best Companies for Leaders” list for 2012.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi Data Systems was recognized among the "Best Companies to Work For" in France and Poland in 2011.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] In 2010 Hitachi Data Systems was accredited by the Best Companies organization in the United Kingdom.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Synchronous TrueCopy causes each write to the primary volume to be performed to the secondary as well, and the I/O is considered complete only when updates to both primary and secondary have been completed.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Asynchronous TrueCopy stores time-stamped IO packets in the primary disk array and transfers them to the secondary array subject to link bandwidth.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] When the primary array's buffer is exhausted, it starts flagging tracks on the primary to be duplicated to the secondary when bandwidth permits.
[src:hitachi-data-systems/hitachi-data-systems] Hitachi Data Systems has four types of partners: Technology, Global Systems Integrators, Hitachi TrueNorth Partners, and Hitachi TrueNorth Advisor Partners.
